Finally, the ratio of single to double b-tagged events, i.e. the ratio of events in SR1 to the sum of events in SR2 and SR3, is sensitive to the b-tagging efficiency. The effect of the b-tagging efficiency is parameterised with a nuisance parameter in the final fit. Since only two b-jets are present in tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$t\bar{t}$$\end{document} events, any additional b-tagged jets originate either from heavy-flavour production in the parton shower or from mistagged c-hadrons. The inclusion of events with more than two b-tags in SR3 gives a small sensitivity to heavy-flavour production in the parton shower.

Several sources of systematic uncertainty affect the tt¯\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
